    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so it's basically a composite material then. since the rebar is buried deep inside the concrete where you can't see it, how do engineers make sure the bond between the two is actually working? like how does the concrete hold onto the steel so it doesn't just slip out when it's under tension?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, you are correct; reinforced concrete functions as a composite material where steel and concrete work together. Engineers ensure the bond is effective through two main methods: the rough texture of rebar created during manufacturing, which provides a superior mechanical \"grip\" against the concrete, and the chemical adhesion (C-S-H gel hydration products) that forms the materials together over time. Special features like ribs integral to the rebar design also help lock the steel in place, preventing it from slipping inside the concrete matrix under both tensile and compressive loads.",
      "source": "target",
